description: When a priest in a shrine in eastern Yoruba country cuts the throat of a sheep or goat before an altar, he holds this cup under the sacrifice's throat to catch its blood. The cup is then emptied over sacred figures or object on a deities figures. If it is for an ancestor buried below the altar, the objects function as groundings or wishes while blood is the electricity carrying the message down to that ancestor.
